<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="127" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[826,1429,1629,1949]" box="[826,1429,1629,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">
<heading box="[826,1429,1629,1653]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" reason="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Von Heyden" authorityYear="1826" box="[826,946,1629,1652]" class="Arachnida" family="Spinturnicidae" genus="Spinturnix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[826,946,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">Spinturnix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
wing mites are haematophagous, perma-
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[826,1429,1629,1949]" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">nent parasites and all life stages are confined to the wing membrane or uropatagium of their host.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[826,1429,1629,1949]" lastBlockId="2.[159,762,311,791]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">
Due to this obligate life history these species make excellent parasites to study host-parasite coevolution and coadaptation. Patterns of coadaptation depend greatly on population structure and gene flow among distinct populations (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Gandon S. &amp; Capowiez Y. &amp; Dubois Y. &amp; Michalakis Y. &amp; Olivieri I." pageId="1" pageNumber="127" pagination="1003 - 1009" refId="ref3023" refString="Gandon S., Capowiez Y., Dubois Y., Michalakis Y., Olivieri I. 1996 - Local adaptation and gene-for-gene coevolution in a metapopulation model - P Roy Soc Lond B Bio, 263: 1003 - 1009. doi: 10.1098 / rspb. 1996.0148" type="journal article" year="1996">
Gandon 
<emphasis box="[826,880,1924,1948]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="127">et al.</emphasis>
, 1996
</bibRefCitation>
), as well as on reproductive mode (
<bibRefCitation author="Barrett L. G. &amp; Thrall P. H. &amp; Burdon J. J. &amp; Linde C. C." lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="1" pageNumber="127" pagination="678 - 685" refId="ref2634" refString="Barrett L. G., Thrall P. H., Burdon J. J., Linde C. C. 2008 - Life history determines genetic structure and evolutionary potential of host-parasite interactions - Trends Ecol Evol, 23: 678 - 685." type="journal article" year="2008">
Barrett 
<emphasis box="[208,262,311,335]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="128">et al.</emphasis>
, 2008
</bibRefCitation>
). As these attributes are difficult to determine directly in small organisms, they require the use of indirect methods such as the use of population genetic markers (
<bibRefCitation author="de Meeus T. &amp; McCoy K. D. &amp; Prugnolle F. &amp; Chevillon C. &amp; Durand P. &amp; Hurtrez-Bousses S. &amp; Renaud F." box="[457,708,416,440]" pageId="2" pageNumber="128" pagination="308 - 332" refId="ref2861" refString="de Meeus T., McCoy K. D., Prugnolle F., Chevillon C., Durand P., Hurtrez-Bousses S., Renaud F. 2007 - Population genetics and molecular epidemiology or how to &quot; debusquer la bete &quot; - Infect Genet Evol, 7: 308 - 332. doi: 10.1016 / j. meegid. 2006.07.003" type="journal article" year="2007">
de Meeus 
<emphasis box="[581,635,416,440]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="128">et al.</emphasis>
, 2007
</bibRefCitation>
). To date no microsatellite markers have been developed for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Von Heyden" authorityYear="1826" box="[202,322,486,509]" class="Arachnida" family="Spinturnicidae" genus="Spinturnix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[202,322,486,509]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="128">Spinturnix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or any other bat ectoparasite. Furthermore, several population genetic studies have encountered problems when studying the Acari due to a strong underrepresentation of dinucleotide repeat microsatellites (
<bibRefCitation author="Navajas M. &amp; Thistlewood H. M. A. &amp; Lagnel J. &amp; Hughes J." box="[426,656,626,651]" pageId="2" pageNumber="128" pagination="249 - 256" refId="ref3315" refString="Navajas M., Thistlewood H. M. A., Lagnel J., Hughes J. 1998 - Microsatellite sequences are underrepresented in two mite-genomes - Insect Mol Bio, 7: 249 - 256. doi: 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2583.1998.00066. x" type="journal article" year="1998">
Navajas 
<emphasis box="[531,585,626,650]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="128">et al.</emphasis>
, 1998
</bibRefCitation>
), as well as non-mendelian transmission of microsatellite alleles (
<bibRefCitation author="de Meeus T. &amp; Humair P. F. &amp; Grunau C. &amp; Delaye C. &amp; Renaud F." box="[226,470,696,721]" pageId="2" pageNumber="128" pagination="943 - 950" refId="ref2926" refString="de Meeus T., Humair P. F., Grunau C., Delaye C., Renaud F. 2004 - Non-Mendelian transmission of alleles at microsatellite loci: an example in Ixodes ricinus, the vector of Lyme disease - Int J Parasitol, 34: 943 - 950. doi: 10.1016 / j. ijpara. 2004.04.006" type="journal article" year="2004">
de Meeus 
<emphasis box="[347,399,696,720]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="128">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
). Here, we report the development of polymorphic dinucleotide repeat microsatellites for two species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Von Heyden" authorityYear="1826" box="[516,636,767,790]" class="Arachnida" family="Spinturnicidae" genus="Spinturnix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[516,636,767,790]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="128">Spinturnix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
